Wash and dry produce.

Drain @pineapple{4%ounce}, reserving juice in a #small bowl{}; roughly chop pineapple. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Quarter @lime{1}. Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1} into strips.

In a second small bowl, combine pineapple, minced onion, half the cilantro, and a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion and green pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned and slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Reduce to medium heat.

Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} to pan with veggies. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in pineapple juice and @Tex-Mex paste{1}; cook until thickened and saucy, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Remove pan from heat and stir in remaining cilantro.

While pork cooks, wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates and fill with pork filling. Top with pineapple salsa and dollop with @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

> Looking for a new way to spice-up your taco Tuesday (or Wednesday... or, any day of the week, really!)? Our chefs put together a sweet and savory version that's sure to satisfy. There's richly-spiced ground pork cooked in pineapple juice, plus charred pepper and onion, a pineapple salsa, and cooling sour cream, all piled into flour tortillas. Taco'bout a great meal.